{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"d65ef32f-b29a-408e-ac5f-d59d5ed053c9","content":"The best approach is **`dotnet-trace`** with the `cpu-sampling` profile. Here's the workflow:\n\n**1. Install the tool inside the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod> -- bash\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-trace\nexport PATH=\"$PATH:$HOME/.dotnet/tools\"\n```\n\n**2. Collect the trace (30s example):**\n```bash\ndotnet-trace collect -p $(pidof dotnet) --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:00:30\n```\n\n**3. Copy the `.nettrace` file out:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:/path/to/trace.nettrace ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**4. Analyze** by opening the `.nettrace` in **Visual Studio**, **PerfView**, or convert to Speedscope format:\n```bash\ndotnet-trace convert trace.nettrace --format Speedscope\n```\nThen open at [speedscope.app](https://www.speedscope.app).\n\n**Tips:**\n- If you can't install tools, use the **sidecar approach** — run `dotnet-trace` from a debug container via `kubectl debug`.\n- For production, prefer `--duration` over manual stop to avoid forgetting a running trace.\n- `dotnet-counters monitor -p $(pidof dotnet)` is a great quick triage step *before* tracing — it shows real-time CPU/GC metrics with zero overhead.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"1f1820d4-3bfc-4292-818b-3715098271ab","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace from a .NET 8 app running in a Kubernetes pod on Linux. This is a knowledge question, not a code task, so I'll answer directly.","outputTokens":412},"id":"8b37a948-aa6b-4016-9c74-bc3c4313ac7d","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:47:50.447Z","parentId":"5ffd1a26-ff04-491c-abf3-7cc759402b20"}
